# Quick Start Guide

Get up and running with Antigravity Workspace in minutes!

## ✅ Prerequisites Check

Before you begin, ensure you have:
- Ubuntu 20.04+ or Debian 11+ (or similar Linux distribution)
- At least 2GB RAM available
- At least 5GB disk space
- Internet connection
- sudo/root access (for installation)

## 🚀 For Ubuntu VPS (Recommended)

### Step 1: Clone and Install

```bash
# Clone the repository
git clone https://github.com/primoscope/antigravity-workspace-template.git
cd antigravity-workspace-template

# Make scripts executable
chmod +x *.sh

# Run automated installation (installs everything you need)
./install.sh
```

The installation script will:
- ✅ Install Node.js, Python, Docker
- ✅ Setup MCP servers
- ✅ Create Python virtual environment
- ✅ Install all dependencies
- ✅ Configure systemd service
- ✅ Setup Nginx reverse proxy (optional)
- ✅ Configure firewall

**Time:** ~5-10 minutes

### Step 1.5: Verify Installation

After installation completes, verify everything is set up correctly:

```bash
# Run the comprehensive test suite
./test-setup.sh
```

This will check:
- ✅ Backend imports successfully
- ✅ All routes are properly configured
- ✅ Frontend files are correct
- ✅ No duplicate routes
- ✅ Configuration files are valid
- ✅ All helper scripts are executable
- ✅ Custom agents are present

**Expected Result:** All tests should pass (100% success rate)

### Step 2: Configure

```bash
# Run interactive configuration wizard
./configure.sh
```

You'll be guided through:
- Gemini AI API key setup
- GitHub token configuration
- Local Ollama setup (optional)
- Optional services (Brave Search, PostgreSQL)
- Server settings

**Time:** ~2-3 minutes

### Step 3: Start

```bash
# Start all services
./start.sh

# Or use systemd
sudo systemctl start antigravity
```

### Step 4: Access

Open your browser:
```
http://your-server-ip/
```

**That's it! You're ready to code with AI! 🎉**

---

## 💻 For Local Development

### Quick Setup (5 minutes)

```bash
# 1. Clone
git clone https://github.com/primoscope/antigravity-workspace-template.git
cd antigravity-workspace-template

# 2. Create virtual environment
python3 -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate  # On Windows: venv\Scripts\activate

# 3. Install Python dependencies
pip install -r requirements.txt
pip install -r backend/requirements.txt

# 4. Install Node.js MCP servers
npm install -g @modelcontextprotocol/server-filesystem
npm install -g @modelcontextprotocol/server-git
npm install -g @github/mcp-server

# 5. Configure
cp .env.example .env
nano .env  # Add your GEMINI_API_KEY

# 6. Start backend
cd backend
python main.py
```

### Access
Open `frontend/index.html` in your browser or go to `http://localhost:8000`

---

## 🐳 For Docker Users

### Using Docker Compose (Easiest)

```bash
# 1. Clone
git clone https://github.com/primoscope/antigravity-workspace-template.git
cd antigravity-workspace-template

# 2. Configure environment
cp .env.example .env
nano .env  # Add your API keys

# 3. Start all services
docker-compose up -d

# 4. View logs
docker-compose logs -f

# 5. Access
# http://localhost:8000
```

### Using Docker (Manual)

```bash
# Build
docker build -t antigravity .

# Run
docker run -d \
  --name antigravity \
  -p 8000:8000 \
  --env-file .env \
  -v $(pwd)/drop_zone:/app/drop_zone \
  -v $(pwd)/logs:/app/logs \
  antigravity

# View logs
docker logs -f antigravity
```

---

## 📋 Verification

After installation, validate your setup:

```bash
# Run validation script
./validate.sh
```

This checks:
- ✅ Python environment
- ✅ Node.js and npm
- ✅ Configuration files
- ✅ Directory structure
- ✅ Custom agents
- ✅ Docker setup
- ✅ Services status

---

## 🎯 First Steps

### 1. Test the Web Interface

1. Open http://localhost:8000 in your browser
2. You should see the enhanced web GUI
3. Try sending a message in the chat

### 2. Use an AI Agent

In the web interface:
1. Select an agent from the right panel (e.g., "Full-Stack Developer")
2. Type: "Create a simple REST API endpoint"
3. Watch the agent respond with code and instructions

### 3. Drop a File

1. Drag and drop a code file into the drop zone area
2. The file will be ingested into the RAG system
3. Ask questions about the file content

### 4. Use GitHub Copilot Integration

In VS Code with GitHub Copilot:
```
@agent:full-stack-developer Create a user authentication system
```

---

## 📖 Common Tasks

### Start Services
```bash
./start.sh
# Or: sudo systemctl start antigravity
# Or: docker-compose up -d
```

### Stop Services
```bash
./stop.sh
# Or: sudo systemctl stop antigravity
# Or: docker-compose down
```

### View Logs
```bash
# Systemd
sudo journalctl -u antigravity -f

# Docker
docker-compose logs -f

# Direct
tail -f logs/backend.log
```

### Update Configuration
```bash
./configure.sh
sudo systemctl restart antigravity  # If using systemd
```

### Check Health
```bash
curl http://localhost:8000/health
curl http://localhost:8000/performance/health
```

---

## 🆘 Troubleshooting

### Port Already in Use
```bash
# Find what's using port 8000
sudo lsof -i :8000

# Kill the process
sudo kill -9 <PID>

# Or change the port in .env
echo "PORT=8001" >> .env
```

### Service Won't Start
```bash
# Check logs
sudo journalctl -u antigravity -xe

# Validate setup
./validate.sh

# Check Python environment
source venv/bin/activate
python -c "import fastapi; print('FastAPI OK')"
```

### Missing Dependencies
```bash
# Reinstall Python deps
source venv/bin/activate
pip install -r requirements.txt --force-reinstall

# Reinstall MCP servers
npm install -g @modelcontextprotocol/server-filesystem --force
```

### Docker Issues
```bash
# Reset Docker environment
docker-compose down -v
docker-compose up -d --build

# Check Docker logs
docker-compose logs backend

# Restart Docker
sudo systemctl restart docker
```

